The defendant Terrance Maurice Cottrell was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of THC (2nd+ Offense), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(e).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Terrance Maurice Cottrell in court with attorney Richard Jeffrey Carpenter.  Zachary A. Wittchow appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  

Court sentenced defendant to serve 1 YEAR in the House of Correction.  Court gives credit for 10 days served. 

Court STAYED sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for 2 YEARS with the following conditions:

- Serve 20 DAYS UP FRONT CONDITION TIME CONSECUTIVE, in the House of Correction.  To be served straight time.
                         
  ***DEFENDANT TAKEN INTO CUSTODY.***

- 60 DAYS, IMPOSED and STAYED, CONSECUTIVE in the House of Correction to be used by the agent for any violations.  Defendant shall serve 10 days for the first violation, 20 days for the second violation, and 30 days for the third violation.

- Complete a mental health evaluation and comply with any recommended treatment.
- AODA assessment and comply with any recommended treatment.
- No controlled substances without a valid prescription, with random drug tests and breathalyzers.  Defendant shall be tested twice per month for the first year, and then be tested once per month, randomly.  
- No association with known drug users or dealers, and no contact at any place where illegal drugs are purchased, used, stored, packaged, or distributed.
- Complete 50 hours of community service.
- Court ordered defendant to provide a DNA, and pay all MANDATORY COURT costs, fees, surcharges, and assessments, while on probation.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means.  Defendant to make regular monthly payments.
- Pay all supervision fees.  Defendant to make regular monthly payments.
